Climate Data Analysis Part 1: Exploring and Organizing Climate Data from Different Sources¶

Introduction¶

Climate change has been studied from a statistical perspective for decades. It has become common knowledge that greenhouse gas emissions contribute to changes in the climate. Especially, the role of CO2 emission has been highlighted as the major indicator of anthropogenic effect on climate change. This notebook will explore historical temperature, volcanic, and co2 data from Berkeley Earth, Total Solar Irradiance Data from SORCE and emission type specific data from CDIAC. After a few interactive plotly visualizations, the disparate .csv and .xlsx files are entered into an SQL-database for easier access and use on the front-end.

Global CO2 emissions by Sector¶

The global increase in CO2 emissions will be explored and visualized first. The historical data comes from The Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center (CDIAC), and the .csv file has data from 1751 to 2014. There are 264 data points, one from every year. The details of modeling historical data before the year 1950 are referenced at CDIAD 2014 Fossil Fuel Overview.

The data cleaning tasks required for this step are:

  1. Renaming columns
  2. Dropping first row of .csv that contains only metadata
  3. Converting strings into floats
  4. Converting the index into a DateTimeIndex
  5. Dropping unneeded columns year and per_capita.

The per-capita data is available only from 1950 onward, and it is more relevant and interesting on its own than in comparison to the sector-specific statistics. Plotly visualizations are awesome. Not only is the combination of Cufflinks, Pandas and Plotly very intuitive and quick for the coder, the resulting time-series plot is fully interactive: the viewer can zoom-in, pan, select and de-select data series to display, etc. without the need of writing custom javascript.

df_emissions_by_sector = pd.read_csv('../data/global.1751_2014.csv')
df_emissions_by_sector.columns = ['year',
             'total',
              'gas_fuel',
              'liquid_fuel',
              'solid_fuel',
              'cement_production',
              'gas_flaring',
             'per_capita']
df_emissions_by_sector.drop(0, inplace=True)
df_emissions_by_sector['total'] = df_emissions_by_sector['total'].astype('float64')
df_emissions_by_sector['gas_fuel'] = df_emissions_by_sector['gas_fuel'].astype('float64')
df_emissions_by_sector.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_emissions_by_sector.year)
df_emissions_by_sector.drop(['year', 'per_capita'], axis=1, inplace=True)
df_emissions_by_sector.info()

                             xTitle='Year',
                             yTitle='Million Metric Tons of C',

As carbon emissions are widely regarded as the most prominent anthropogenic factor in climate change, the steep rise in emissions from 1950 is definitely noteworthy. The graph also highlights the proportions of different fuel sources. Solid fuel (mostly coal) dominates until the late 1960's, after which oil use surpasses. Most recently the heavy use of solid fuels surpassed liquid fuel in terms of total global emissions. While it may sound like a race, winning it is quite the questionable honor.

CO2, Volcanic, and Sun Forcing¶

The next visualization uses historical temperature, volcanic, and co2 data from Berkeley Earth and total solar irradiance data from SORCE. The multi-sheet .xlsx-file from Berkeley Earth is a bit hard to work with, as the relevant data is spread across different sheets, and there is a lot of empty space and metadata at the top of the files. The procedure for getting the relevant information into a dataframe include:

  1. Import the relevant sheet of the excel file
  2. Find the relevant columns of the sheet
  3. Drop the rows that contain only metadata
  4. Rename the columns
  5. Change the datatypes
  6. Set the index to year
In [4]:
df_co2 = pd.read_excel('../data/forcing-comparison.xlsx', sheet_name=0)
df_co2 = df_co2[['Berkeley Interpolated', 'Unnamed: 17']].drop([0, 1, 2])
df_co2.columns = ['year', 'co2']
df_co2['year'] = df_co2['year'].astype('float64')
df_co2['co2'] = df_co2['co2'].astype('float64')
df_co2.index = df_co2.year
In [5]:
df_temp = pd.read_excel('../data/forcing-comparison.xlsx', sheet_name=2, skiprows=[0, 1])
df_temp = df_temp[['Year', 'Temperature (C) ']]
df_temp.columns = ['year', 'temperature']
df_temp.index = df_temp['year']
In [6]:
df_volcanic = pd.read_excel('../data/forcing-comparison.xlsx', sheet_name=1)
df_volcanic = df_volcanic[['12-month Moving Average', 'Unnamed: 20']].drop([0, 1, 2, 3])
df_volcanic.columns = ['year', 'volcanic_12m_average']
df_volcanic = df_volcanic.astype('float64')
df_volcanic.index = df_volcanic['year']
In [7]:
df_solar = pd.read_csv('../data/TSI_Data.csv', sep=';')
df_solar.columns = ['year', 'total_solar']
df_solar.index = df_solar['year']

Combining into one dataframe and plotting¶

After isolating the relevant information into separate dataframes, the data is concatenated into one dataframe. As the years, which are given as decimal numbers do not line up perfectly across the dataset, the gaps are filled with previous observations of the feature. This ensures a smooth graphing, and works as a sensible work-around.

In [8]:
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar = pd.concat([df_temp, df_co2, df_volcanic, df_solar], ignore_index=True, sort=True)
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.sort_values('year', inplace=True)
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.fillna(method=('ffill'), inplace=True)
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.index = df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar['year']

One more step is required before the plot can be made sense of: normalization. The absolute values of the measurements work on such different scales, that plotting them as-is produces a pretty non-sensical description of the data. This plot can be seen below. Underneath the nonsensical plot, the normalized variant is provided. It is scaled with the mean and unit variance of the data, similarly to the StandardScaler() of Scikit-Learn, and the starting point is set to the minimum and maximum values of the future target variable: Avg. Temperature.

In [9]:
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.drop('year', axis=1).iplot(title='What am I looking at? Absolute levels of avg. Temperature, CO2 Concentration, Solar Irradiance and Volcanic Activity',
                                         xTitle='Year',
                                         yTitle='Level',
                                         theme='ggplot',
                                         colorscale='set1')
In [10]:
normalized_df = (df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar-df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.mean())/df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.std()
normalized_df = normalized_df.loc[(normalized_df.index > df_temp.year.min()) & (normalized_df.index < df_temp.year.max())]
In [11]:
normalized_df.drop('year', axis=1).iplot(title='Standardized levels of avg. Temperature, CO2 Concentration, Solar Irradiance and Volcanic Activity',
                                         xTitle='Year',
                                         yTitle='Standardized Level',
                                         theme='ggplot',
                                         colorscale='set1')

That's more like it! With data that looks like this, it seems feasible that these features can be modeled both for explanatory power (Statstools OLS Linear Regression) and prediction (Scikit-Learn Regression Models) with regards to the target: global average temperature.

Saving to an SQL Database¶

At this point, it would be possible to save our dataframe to a .csv-file, but for wider production, it is good to establish a database. It will be easier to expand the dataset with additional findings later, if the database is a structured source for all available data. Using the great SQLAlchemy package, we establish a local file-based SQLite db connection (geo_data.db file to our data-folder), and save our dataframe, with the non-normalized values, as a table called Geo_Time_Series. Switching from the local file to an SQL-server in future will be trivial, thanks to SQLAlchemy doing most of the heavy lifting for us.

In [12]:
from sqlalchemy import create_engine

engine = create_engine('sqlite:///../data/geo_data.db')
In [13]:
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar_to_database = df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.loc[(df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.index > df_temp.year.min()) & (df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar.index < df_temp.year.max())]
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar_to_database.drop('year', axis=1,inplace=True)
In [14]:
df_temp_co2_volcanic_solar_to_database.to_sql('Geo_Time_Series', con=engine, if_exists='replace', index=True)
